Did you know that last year in the Inflation Reduction Act, Congress put in a LOT of tax credits to help make it more affordable to make green upgrades in your life? 🌎 You can even get up to $4,000 towards a USED electric vehicle!
.
Right now credits are out there for things like solar panels (& installation), upgrading your windows and doors, heat pumps and more. Later this year we expect even MORE credits to be rolled out for appliances like electrified ovens & stoves (🤭).
.
To get info on the updated credits as they’re released, sign up for the emails at WhiteHouse.Gov/CleanEnergy
.
There is still SO much work to be done, and we must keep going to secure continued major infrastructure investments in items like high-speed rail, public transit, walkable cities, and more. But for now, here’s something that can benefit the public right away! And make sure you share this info with anyone you know considering making their home greener, more weatherized or considering a switch to eco-friendly appliances!

Let’s examine one of the GOP’s disturbing core arguments yesterday: that criticism of US/Israeli gov’s role in the Palestinian human rights crisis, which orgs from @humanrightswatch to @amnesty are sounding the alarm on, is equivalent to antisemitism.
.
It is important to recognize that this is a dangerous and false conflation designed to threaten and prevent us from taking the matter of human rights in the region seriously. Jewish members of Congress themselves, of all positions and takes on the matter, conveyed horror at the charge of antisemitism being cynically weaponized to silence people in this fashion and testified to @ilhanmn’s character. They asked the GOP to not do this in their name nor on their community’s behalf.
.
It also gets to one of the actual core reasons they sought to strip @ilhanmn of her committee assignment to Foreign Affairs: because her experience as a refugee, Muslim, immigrant, mother, and survivor of war gives her a unique and special credibility to challenge a US foreign policy consensus that has too often failed both Americans at home and human beings abroad. Her presence, identity, and experience forces us to look in the mirror and sit with our policy decisions and costs of war, and center the victims, survivors, and those who are most impacted.
.
That is why it is important to show up and support in this moment, and see this cynical political attack for what it really is: fear of inspiring a larger shift towards accountability and transparency by everyday Americans regarding our own foreign policy.

Solidarity with screenwriters! 

This past Tuesday, The Writers Guild of America went on strike to demand better treatment from production studios. They are fighting to secure fair wages as studio profit increases dramatically. 

Production budgets have sharply increased, while pay for writers has declined by 4% over the past decade — 23% when adjusted for inflation. 
Today Team @aoc dropped off sandwiches and wraps for striking workers at Silvercup Studios in Queens. You can support their efforts too! 

Stand in Solidarity with @WGA by taking one of the following actions: 

💪 Donate funds for snacks to strikers in LA through @dsa_la 
💪 Join writers at the picket line.
💪 Donate to the Entertainment Community Fund @alifeinthearts 
💪 Amplify @wgaeast and @wgawest message on social media.
💪 Don’t cross the picket line. You may start to see online calls for ‘pitch contests’ or ‘fan casting’ – avoid them! These can sometimes be ways for studios or producers to crowdsource ideas from the public for free and circumvent the union.

The thing is, people of upper class and racial privilege have long enjoyed their own “affirmative action” across much of society - not only in college admissions. Who gets educational, investment, housing / job opportunities, cultural cachet and beyond have always reflected power dynamics around race and class in the United States. Today’s ruling reflects that long, regressive tradition. The Supreme Court protected themselves and their patrons from scrutiny of their own class and racial privilege, while dismantling the very few efforts exerted to address race inequality in college admissions. Class solidarity among the 1% is very real, and that’s what this Supreme Court decision represents. This only deepens the necessity for a multiracial working class to band together - today especially for tuition-free public college + vocational education.
SCOTUS did not strike down Biden’s authority to cancel student debt. We can and must move forward before the payment pause lifts.
The Supreme Court has given up their legitimacy in exchange for billionaire fishing trips and their authority should be treated accordingly.

Last month I had the honor of leading the first all-Spanish speaking US Congressional delegation to Latin America. 🇺🇸 We visited Brazil, Chile, and Colombia in a historic effort to both acknowledge the harmful history of US interventionism and explore opportunities for a path of mutual respect and collaboration into the future.

.

.
Since our return, we have made significant progress on the declassification of US documents related to the 1973 Chilean coup, are working to fulfill the US’s $500M commitment to the Amazon Fund in Brazil, and deepening our commitment to frontline indigenous and Afro-Colombian communities in Colombia as efforts are made towards peace.

STUDENT LOAN GUIDE PART 1 of 6: INTRODUCTION

The fight for student loan cancellation IS ALIVE and we are making progress. However, LOTS of you have been sending me questions about payments restarting on October 1st, including about newly announced programs and basic logistics. In that light, we have put together a 6 part playlist guide to answer some of your most common questions and help people navigate the boatloads of information while we continue to organize. Please note that this is NOT an endorsement of loans restarting, but merely a transmission of basic facts and essential info since there’s a lot of mistaken claims floating around and we want to make sure people have access to the facts.
.
PART 1: INTRO
PART 2: POLITICS/CONTEXT FOR RESTART DATE
PART 3: YOU COULD BE ELIGIBLE FOR CANCELLATION RIGHT NOW AND NOT KNOW IT
PART 4: REDUCING OR ELIMINATING YOUR LOAN PAYMENT WITH THE NEW SAVE PROGRAM
PART 5: HOW TO ACTUALLY MAKE A PAYMENT AND WHAT HAPPENS IF YOU DON’T
PART 6: HOW TO REPORT LOAN PROCESSORS WHO ARE MISHANDLING YOUR LOAN
.

STUDENT LOAN GUIDE PART 2/6: HOW DID WE GET HERE?
.
There’s a lot of confusion out there as to whether cancellation is still alive, what the status of it is, and why payments are restarting. This video briefly runs through the timeline of events from the first cancellation announcement, to SCOTUS, to payments restarting. If you’ve heard a lot of on/off about the program in the news, this should put that into context and answer some of those questions. This is NOT an endorsement of payments restarting, but recounting the sequence of events and summarizing where we are now since we’ve seen some confusion out there. If you want to jump straight into questions about your loans, check out part 3 and beyond.

STUDENT LOAN GUIDE PART 3/6: YOU COULD BE ELIGIBLE FOR LOAN CANCELLATION *NOW* AND NOT KNOW IT
.
While the fight for broader student loan cancellation continues (and we should expect updates on that over the next year), there ARE certain categories of people who are eligible for cancellation programs NOW. Namely: public service (gov/nonprofit), teachers, permanent disability, and those who were either misled by their colleges or had their colleges close down during or shortly after graduating.
.
Additionally, a LOT of people were unjustly turned away from prior PSLF requests. Many of those cases are being reviewed now for reassessment/cancellation.

STUDENT LOAN GUIDE PT 4/6: ELIMINATING/REDUCING YOUR STUDENT LOAN PAYMENT WITH THE NEW SAVE PROGRAM
.
In addition to continuing to pursue broader loan cancellation, the Biden Admin also announced a new loan program called SAVE that could lower or eliminate your loan payments - even if you’ve already been on another income-driven repayment program previously. This video explains what it is and how to sign up or learn more.

STUDENT LOAN GUIDE PT 5/6: WHAT HAPPENS IF I DON’T PAY AND HOW DO YOU EVEN START?
.
While we disagree with lifting of the payment pause, LOTS of people are asking about where to even start after 3 years of suspended payments. After you check if you’re eligible for the current loan cancellation and payment reduction/elimination programs, this video will walk you through some of the basic facts and logistics. While is not an endorsement of payments restarting, we do think it’s important that people have the facts. So here it is!
.
Next up: what to do if your loan servicer is acting strange or misbehaving

STUDENT LOAN GUIDE PT 6/6: WHAT TO DO IF YOUR LOAN SERVICER IS MISHANDLING YOUR ACCOUNT
.
It is VERY important to document if your loan servicer is mishandling your account or making mistakes. In the past, loan servicers who mishandled loans resulted in over student loan cancellation for people impacted. It also helps officials keep an eye 👁️ out for bad actors and pursue accountability and oversight. So: document, document, document! This last video installment will show you how.
.
Thank you for sticking along! Was this series helpful? If so, how? Are there other areas you’d like to see video guides on? Feel free to share with others and drop questions in the comments. ⬇️

For the 1st time in US history, the Speaker of the House has been removed (and by his own party, no less). How did this happen and what does this mean?

“But why didn’t Dems vote for the Republican Speaker??” Same reason Republicans didn’t vote for the Republican Speaker. He was not good at his job. (And supports taking away women’s rights, among many other things)

To help solve the migrant crisis, the US must deal with the root causes and our contributions to it: namely, the destabilizing role that broad-based US sanctions are playing in displacing millions of poor and working class people across South America than the decision-makers they claim to target. In fact, the same year the Rubio-Trump sanctions were put into place was also the year we started to see ballooning migrant waves along our southern border - as well as the borders of other nations.
.
To be clear, sanctions are not the sole factor in this situation, but they are a major and recent one within our control. Any conversation about “solving” the migrant crisis that omits Latin America (and other regions migrants are coming from) and how US foreign policy engages it is woefully incomplete. It is time to seriously reckon with the complexities of the source and how US foreign policy engages that reality. We should also demand more from our media and governance, which spends far too little time on the root causes and too much on reactive yet superficial discussions about the border.

Our movement fights for Palestinian human rights AND protects the safety of our Jewish brothers, sisters, and siblings.
.
Palestinians and those who advocate for them are NOT equivalent to Hamas. Israelis and those concerned for Jewish safety are NOT equivalent to the acts of the Israeli government. If we cannot stand consistently against all forms of bigotry, we risk standing for nothing at all.
.
Now more than ever, we must check antisemitism, Islamophobia, racism, and xenophobia wherever we see it. We cannot allow hatred to gain momentum in the fight for human rights and dignity. Stating one value does not invalidate others. This moment is about expanding our context and protecting one another.
.
The pursuit of justice requires us to recognize that all human dignity is intertwined. Ours is the fight to unite our common humanity in the face of lesser instincts - so that we may prevail in the pursuit of peace, safety, justice, freedom, and prosperity for all.

Over the last month or two, I have been grappling with the declining health and recent passing of my abuela (hence my absence here and online generally lately). I’d like to take a moment here to celebrate her. My abuela moved from Puerto Rico to New York to help raise me, and after all her grandchildren grew into adulthood she moved back home to nuestra isla🇵🇷 where we all continued to return and gather ever since.
.
My abuela was an unbelievably strong woman, which despite her age or ailing, had given her passing a certain air of impossibility. What she experienced throughout her life - from working tobacco fields as a child, making a living on her own, raising five children in PR, moving to a new land and language to raise her grandchildren, and returning home to ascend and enjoy the sweetness and accomplishment of her rightful perch as matriarch - is nothing short of remarkable.
.
My abuela had a green thumb that was practically magic, and coaxed life, food, and beauty out of the ground in every climate from the Caribbean to the Bronx to nourish her family. She had a ruthless sense of humor and could take a joke like no other.  She was always both the toughest and most tender person in the room. And she gave so many people so much. 
.
I am and have been heartbroken, but I am also tremendously grateful to have had her as my abuela. She got to see things my dad didn’t get to see, like my graduation from college, navigating my first adult job, and getting elected to Congress. And while those events and accomplishments mattered, they were far from what was most important to her. Down to our last goodbye, what she always cared about most was that her children and grandchildren were decent people who tried their best to be good to others every day. She measured our success by humility, kindness, mercy, humor, and effort. My abuela was so many different women over her lifetime, and taught me that I could be, and bloom, too. She taught me that practically nothing is insurmountable, that we are all impossible in the first place, and we should both be grateful for all that we have and determined in pursuing our dreams. We were lucky to have her.
.
Te amo Tatita. 🕊️
